<br>
First exposure to non-Iksar.... fear and lothing, disgust at their weakness both physical and moral. First exposure being the short pointy-eared invaders of Kunark, both blueskinned and pale. Forced to interact with some, to obtain needed supplies far from home, encounters language barriers. Chose to learn some languages, rather than starve. More interaction with non-Iksar learning their tongues. Sees some admirable traits in a few of these softskins, begins to wonder.<br>
<br>
Interaction becomes more frequent, actually hunts with some softskins. Sees more admirable examples of all races, as well as the vile disgusting softskins who are spoken of by the Elders. Wonders at the dichotomy. First stirrings of pity for these less than Iksar beings.<br>
<br>
Forms a guild with some friends, who bring along some non-Iksar &quot;friends&quot; of theirs... a disturbing concept, but his friends are Iksar, so to be trusted.<br>
<br>
Meets a curious Human who sometimes claims to be an Iksar, trapped in the body of a human, sometimes claims to be Karana's Cleric to the Iksar, sent to convert the Empire. Obviously insane, but with some small talent as a healer.<br>
<br>
Meets an Iksar who claims to be a Goblin, in the guise of an Iksar. Obviously insane, perhaps addled as an egg. She shows great prowess as a priestess, first true non-creche friend.<br>
<br>
For a long period, hunting and training far from home, has little interaction with Iksar. Forced to interact more with the softskins, decides since they are to be slaves, they can be used, but sees more and more that is worthy of respect in some. Learns many tongues, masters a few. Truely begins to wonder at the dictates of his Elders. Comes to befriend some of these non-Iksar, long period of confusion.<br>
<br>
Spends much time hunting alone, both near to home and far afield. Spends much time thinking about the Empire, and the softskins. Does not so much have an epiphany, as reaches a conclusion:<br>
<br>
Still numbers many not of the Empire as friends, but realizes that the vision of the Elders is right, even his friends must one day be slaves to the Empire. But also believes the Elders are wrong, slaves can contribute to the Empire, they are like any other possession, some are useful, to be cherished, others not so useful, to be used up.<br>
<br>
Sees no contridiction, other than with the beliefs of his fellow Iksar. Still seeks to solve this contradiction, as he is viewed as less than whole by many within the Empire, but still believes there is some worth in some non-Iksar.<br>
<br>
Xethux<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
